%[text] # Mixed frequency model
%[text] **WARNING (BEAR 6 / BEARX): The structural identification cell at the bottom of this notebook (Cholesky on top of MixedFrequency) currently fails with a dimension-mismatch error inside mixed.estimator.MixedFrequency/initializeSampler/sampler line 217 (Phat = GAMMAs \* Pt1 \* GAMMAs' + ...). Root cause: the Kalman closure variable Pmean is only set inside one branch of the recursion around line 364, so on a second sampler invocation Pt = Pmean can be empty or wrongly sized. This is an upstream toolbox bug, not a tutorial issue. The reduced-form path (modelR1.presample) works fine. See test6\_mixedFrequency.m and BEARX\_PATCHES.md §1bis for details.**
%[text] **DATA NOTE: mixed\_frequency\_data\_transformed.csv has the low-frequency series ygdp forward-filled to every month. mixed.estimator.MixedFrequency expects NaN on non-quarter-end rows. Add this snippet after the tablex.fromFile call to mask the forward-fill: months = month(inputTbl.Time); inputTbl.ygdp(~ismember(months,\[3,6,9,12\])) = NaN;**
%[text:tableOfContents]{"heading":"**Table of Contents**"}
%%
%[text] ## Housekeeping
clear
close all
  
import mixed.*
%%
%[text] ## Convenience functions
%[text] The `extremesFunc` function compresses any number of samples (draws from the posterior) into two numbers - the minimum and the maximum.
percentiles = [10, 50, 90];

prctileFunc = @(x) prctile(x, percentiles, 2);

extremesFunc = @(x) [min(x, [], 2), max(x, [], 2)];

medianFunc = @(x) median(x, 2);

defaultColors = get(0, "defaultAxesColorOrder");
%%
%[text] ## Number of Samples
numPresampled = 1000;
%%
%[text] ## Prepare meta information for the models
%[text] The meta information is almost identical to that of the base model, except that it distinguishes between two types of endogenous variables:
%[text] **highFrequencyNames** – names of high-frequency variables; their frequency determines the frequency of the final model (currently, only monthly data are supported).
%[text] **lowFrequencyNames** – names of low-frequency variables (currently, only quarterly data are supported).
%[text] **Important note**: the model does not allow the presence of exogenous variables other than the intercept.

estimStart = datex.m(2001,1);
estimEnd = datex.m(2021,2);
estimSpan = datex.span(estimStart, estimEnd);

meta = Meta( ...
    highFrequencyNames=["ipi", "ZEW", "DAX", "ifoclimate",...
        "ifoexpectations", "Retail", "Manufacturingsales",...
    	"Autprod", "Worldtrade", "WorldIP"], ...
    lowFrequencyNames="ygdp", ...
    order=6, ...
    intercept=true, ...
    estimationSpan=estimSpan, ...
    identificationHorizon=12 ...
);

%%
%[text] ## Specifying and loading input data
inputTbl = tablex.fromFile("data/mixed_frequency_data_transformed.csv");

% Keep ygdp only at the end of each quarter (Mar/Jun/Sep/Dec).
months = month(inputTbl.Time);
isQuarterEnd = ismember(months, [3, 6, 9, 12]);
inputTbl.ygdp(~isQuarterEnd) = NaN;

dataH = DataHolder(meta, inputTbl);
%%
%[text] ## Estimation/sampling of the reduced form model 
%[text] 
%[text] Similarly to plain BVARs the mixed frequency model also have 5 hyperparameters which are used for generating Minnesota type dummy observation
%[text] **MixedLambda1 (0.1) –** Overall tightness, controls overall shrinkage of coefficients toward prior means.
%[text] **MixedLambda2 (3.4) –** Lag decay, governs how rapidly higher-lag coefficients are shrunk
%[text] **MixedLambda3 (1) –** Covariance tightness, strength of prior on residual covariance structure.
%[text] **MixedLambda4 (3.4) –** Constant tightness, shrinkage applied to the intercept term.
%[text] **MixedLambda5 (14.76) –** Cross-variable shrinkage, controls correlation strength across variable coefficients.
%[text] 
estimatorR1 = estimator.MixedFrequency(meta) %[output:46fd84a8]

modelR1 = ReducedForm( ...
    meta=meta ...
    , dataHolder=dataH ...
    , estimator=estimatorR1 ...
);

modelR1.initialize();
info0 = modelR1.presample(numPresampled); %[output:4217dcdf]
modelR1.Presampled{1}.beta %[output:8a53ec5d]

%% NOTE on the structural identification step
% The original t6_mixedFrequency.mlx Live Script continues with a Cholesky
% identification cell:
%
%   identChol = identifier.Cholesky(ordering=[]);
%   modelS1   = Structural(reducedForm=modelR1, identifier=identChol);
%   modelS1.initialize();
%   modelS1.presample(numPresampled);
%
% That cell fails with a dimension-mismatch error inside
% mixed.estimator.MixedFrequency/initializeSampler/sampler (line 217):
%   Phat = GAMMAs * Pt1 * GAMMAs' + GAMMAu * sig_qq * GAMMAu';
%
% Root cause: the Kalman filter closure stores Pmean only inside one branch
% of the recursion (around line 364). On a second sampler invocation -
% which the structural identifier triggers via redSampler() - Pt is
% restored from Pmean, which can be [] or wrongly sized. This is an
% upstream toolbox bug in mixed.estimator.MixedFrequency, not in the
% tutorial. Reduced-form mixed-frequency works fine, so this script
% intentionally stops here.

fprintf("\ntest6_mixedFrequency completed (reduced-form only).\n");
%%
%[text] ## Running Unconditional forecast 
%[text] 
%[text] ### Setting up the forecast range and run the forecast
fcastStart = datex.shift(modelR1.Meta.EstimationEnd, -10); %The forecast starts 10 periods prior to the end of the estimation span.
fcastEnd = datex.shift(modelR1.Meta.EstimationEnd, 0); %The forecast ends at the end of the estimation window.
fcastSpan = datex.span(fcastStart, fcastEnd);

fcastStart, fcastEnd %[output:4a867ef0] %[output:11aeabb3]

fcastTbx = modelR1.forecast(fcastSpan);
fcastPrctileTbx = tablex.apply(fcastTbx, prctileFunc);
fcastPrctileTbx = tablex.flatten(fcastPrctileTbx); %keeping only the pctiles set at the beginning of the file (10, 50, 90)


%[text] ### Visualize the unconditional forecast
% 
% chartpack.forecastPercentiles( ...
%     fcastPrctileTbx, modelR1, FigureTitle ="Unconditional forecast")
%%
%[text] ## Identification
%[text] 
%[text] ### Cholesky
%[text] You can use the Cholesky decomposition also with a different ordering of endogenous variables than in the meta specification. However, if the trailing part of the order matches the meta order, you may omit that portion.
%[text] 
%[text] #### Setting up the identifier

identChol = identifier.Cholesky(ordering=[]); 

modelS1 = Structural(reducedForm=modelR1, identifier=identChol);
modelS1.initialize();

info0 = modelS1.presample(numPresampled); %[output:812b1179]
modelS1.Presampled{1} %[output:1ca1ffed]

%[text] #### 
%[text] #### Checking transition matrices
modelS1.Presampled{1}.IdentificationDraw %[output:67ad26fd]
modelS1.Presampled{1}.IdentificationDraw.A{1,1} %[output:6aab9688]
modelS1.Presampled{1}.IdentificationDraw.A{2,1} %[output:8373f3de]
%[text] #### 
%[text] #### Checking scaling matrix
modelS1.Presampled{1}.D %[output:78883110]
modelS1.Presampled{2}.D %[output:1c31731c]
%[text] ### 
%%
%[text] ## Impulse responses (IRF)
%[text] ### 
%[text] ### Cholesky
respTbl1 = modelS1.simulateResponses(); %[output:11eb679c]
respTbl1 = tablex.apply(respTbl1, prctileFunc);
respTbl1 = tablex.flatten(respTbl1);

respTbl1 %[output:72091eff]

chartpack.responsePercentiles( ... %[output:group:336d06fb] %[output:00352fe8]
    respTbl1, modelS1 ... %[output:00352fe8]
    , "figureTitle", "Shock response of Cholesky (percentiles)" ... %[output:00352fe8]
); %[output:group:336d06fb] %[output:00352fe8]
%[text] ### 
%%
%[text] ## **Historical shock decomposition**
%[text] 
histContTbx = modelS1.calculateContributions();

histContMedTbx = tablex.apply(histContTbx, medianFunc);

chartpack.contributionsMedian( ... %[output:group:2ff52fc6] %[output:4e109a92]
    histContMedTbx, modelS1 ... %[output:4e109a92]
    , "figureTitle", "Shock contributions with Cholesky (median)" ... %[output:4e109a92]
); %[output:group:2ff52fc6] %[output:4e109a92]
%%
%[text] ## **Unconditional forecast shock decomposition**
%[text] 

[uncFcastTbl1, uncFcastContribTbl1] = modelS1.forecast( ...
    fcastSpan, ...
    contributions=true ...
);


contMedTbx = tablex.apply(uncFcastContribTbl1, medianFunc);

chartpack.contributionsMedian( ... %[output:group:322e9f7c] %[output:5a98da2b]
    contMedTbx, modelS1 ... %[output:5a98da2b]
    , "figureTitle", "Unconditional forecast Shock contributions with Cholesky (median)" ... %[output:5a98da2b]
); %[output:group:322e9f7c] %[output:5a98da2b]

%%
%[text] ## **FEVD**
fevdTbx = modelS1.calculateFEVD(); %[output:98dfd057]

fevdMedTbx = tablex.apply(fevdTbx, medianFunc);

chartpack.contributionsMedian( ... %[output:group:08b7bd58] %[output:251c2aa1]
    fevdMedTbx, modelS1 ... %[output:251c2aa1]
    , "figureTitle", "FEVD (median)" ... %[output:251c2aa1]
); %[output:group:08b7bd58] %[output:251c2aa1]


